replying to M. Devilliers et al. Nature Geoscience https://doi.org/10.1038/s41561-026-02028-8 (2026)We thank Devilliers et al. for their comment1. We first clarify that our original article2 investigated inter-basin oceanic teleconnections of the Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation (AMOC) and whether subarctic freshening can improve model-data agreement of direct and indirect AMOC estimates. The key findings of our article were as follows: (1) changes in AMOC strength rapidly propagate across the oceans via planetary waves, which generate surface warming and salinification in the eastern and western South Atlantic on distinct timescales; (2) applying new wave-fingerprint indices to observational datasets reveals a statistically significant AMOC weakening since the mid-twentieth century; and (3) simulating subarctic freshening in historical simulations since 1960 improves AMOC data-model agreement.



