Weakening of the Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation driven by subarctic freshening since the mid-twentieth century

Gabriel M. PontesLaurie Menviel

Nature Geoscience

        Article


            18 Nov 2024

Brief Communication

Published: 25 June 2026

Declining tropical sea surface temperature variability under post-2050s greenhouse warming
                    Guojian Wang 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0002-8881-73941,2,3 & Agus Santoso 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0001-7749-81241,2,4

Nature Climate Change

(2026) Cite this article









            Save article




                View saved research

Subjects

            Atmospheric dynamicsPhysical oceanographyProjection and prediction

AbstractTropical climate variability, including the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, Indian Ocean Dipole and Atlantic Niño/Niña variability, has long governed global interannual climate fluctuations. Understanding how their influence may change in the next few decades is critically important for climate prediction and adaptation. Here we show that tropical interannual sea surface temperature variability could start to weaken in the next few decades, even if greenhouse warming intensifies.

