bility trend.Extended Data Fig. 2 Influence of model biases on the time evolution of tropical SST variability.a, Time evolution in Niño3.4 SST variability based on selected models (Supplementary Table 1) that can simulate realistic ENSO nonlinearity5. b, As in a, but for non-selected models. c and d, The same as a and b, but for IOD based on IOD nonlinearity as model selection criteria6. e and f, The same as a and b, but for Atlantic Niño/Niña based on mean state simulation as model selection criteria4. Note that the non-selected models may include models that are not assessed by the past studies.Extended Data Fig. 3 Projected changes in tropical SST variability under historical and SSP1-2.6 emission scenarios.a, Time evolution of DJF ENSO (Niño3.4; 170°W-120°W, 5°S-5°N) interannual variability (°C) (solid line with shading) based on all available CMIP6 models under the historical and SSP1-2.6 emission scenarios (see Supplementary Table 1) using a 31-year running window. The shading shows the range of one s.d. of the multi-model ensemble mean in each year based on a bootstrap test. The multi-colored curve corresponding to the right Y axis represents the evolution of the 31-years trend of ENSO variability (°C per 100 years), with colors representing percentage of models agreeing on the sign of the multi-model ensemble mean of the trend. b, and c, As in a, but for SON DMI index (50°E-70°E, 10°S-10°N minus 90°E-110°E, 10°S-0°N) and JJA ATL3 index (3°S-3°N, 20°W-0°), respectively.Supplementary informationSupplementary Information (download PDF )Supplementary Table 1.Peer Review File (download PDF )Rights and permissionsSpringer Nature or its licensor (e.g. a society or other partner) holds exclusive rights to this article under a publishing agreement with the author(s) or other rightsholder(s); author self-archiving of the accepted manuscript version of this article is solely governed by the terms of such publishing agreement and applicable law.Reprints and permissionsA